properties.abstract: From Flüelen they look like two almost identical pictures of the same mountain: the Bauenstöcke. From a close range, however, Niderbauen Chulm (formerly called «Seelisbergerkulm») and Oberbauenstock («Baberg») turn out to be totally different characters, in terms of hiking as well as the landscape, which makes the traverse even more interesting. This is a Lake Lucerne tour par excellence, due to the central position directly above the lake.
properties.subtitle: Bauenstöcke: neighbours, but very different from each other
properties.title: Traverse from Niderbauen Chulm to Stockhütte

sac_photos.title: To the left of the rocky Oberbauenstock the gentle dome of Niderbauen Chulm is visible.
The scrambling passages on the ascent to Oberbauenstock.
A long, mostly grassy ridge leads from Oberbauenstock to Lückli.

segments.description: From the Alp Weid summit station hike south-westward on the marked trail in the pasture. Slightly more steeply ascend past a cabin to the beautifully located Lauweli (1528 m).
segments.title: Alp Weid – Lauweli

segments.description: From Lauweli continue to ascend and past large boulders traverse a talus above the alp to aim at the distinct breach to the left below Niderbauen Chulm. Iron pegs help to climb the 1½ metres of the first rocky outcrop. Afterwards an iron stair leads up to a cave. Through the cave a 20 metre high iron ladder leads to the grassy gully, in which a good path zigzags up to the saddle north-east of Gütsch. Now in a few minutes hike up to Niderbauen Chulm (1923 m).

photos.caption: View from Oberbauenstock back to Niderbauen Chulm. To the right of the talus below the rock face is Lauweli.

segments.title: Lauweli – Niderbauen Chulm

segments.description: From Niderbauen Chulm descend west or east of Gütsch in moderately steep pastures to the bifurcation at P. 1626 («Merlieggen»). From here on a large trail hike to a distinct saddle (1599 m), then climb up some wooden stairs to P. 1761.
segments.title: Niderbauen Chulm – P. 1761

segments.description: At the signpost at 1761 m the white-blue-white marked trail begins, leading on the sometimes precipitous grassy face to the grassy shoulder at P. 1882. Traverse the following talus southward. Now a steep schrofen and rock face with good holds offering grade I climbing passages makes the access to the south-west ridge possible. From here a distinct path winds up slightly to the right of the ridge, thus in the south face, to Oberbauenstock.

photos.caption: The scrambling passages on the ascent to Oberbauenstock.

segments.title: P. 1761 – Oberbauenstock

segments.description: From the summit descend on the same route. However, we leave the shady face of the ascent to the right and hike on the long ridge, sometimes slightly below the ridge line in the south face to Lückli (1877 m) below Zingel.

photos.caption: A long, mostly grassy ridge leads from Oberbauenstock to Lückli.

segments.title: Oberbauenstock – Lückli

segments.description: From Lückli descend through to the ruin at P. 1650, then continue via Chruteren and somewhat roughly (T3+) to the lower trail. As the trail charted in the map via Rigital, Stelli and Lochhütte is hardly maintained, increasingly overgrown and often slippery, branch off right at the bifurcation at about 1450 m to Wandeli and reach Ronen via Haseneggli. From there walk to Stockhütte on a dull road (called «Rinderbühl» on the map).

photos.caption: After Lückli the route goes through comfortable terrain at the foot of Schwalmis.

segments.title: Lückli – Stockhütte
